2026-06-16 | Final Array After Insert and Global XOR Operations

	Question
Process all queries and return the final sorted array.
	Key Insight
Instead of immediately applying every XOR operation to all elements:
		maintain a global XOR value
say:
		xr
Whenever we see:
		1 x
just do:
		xr ^= x
This means every stored element is logically XORed by xr.
For insertion:
		0 x
we need to store the value in a way that future XORs are handled correctly.
If current global XOR is xr:
		store
			x ^ xr
Why?
Later final value becomes:
			(x ^ xr) ^ xr
			= x
Thus all insertions remain correct.
After processing all queries:
		actual value =
		stored value ^ xr
Apply this to every element and sort.
	Approach
1.	Initialize:
			arr = {0}
			xr = 0
2.	For each query:
		if type == 0
				store (x ^ xr)
		if type == 1
				xr ^= x
3.	Convert stored values to actual values:
				val = stored ^ xr
4.	Sort the resulting array.
5.	Return it.
	Time Complexity
	O(q + n log n)
	where n is final array size.
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> constructArray(vector<vector<int>>& queries) {
        vector<int> arr;
        arr.push_back(0);
        int xr = 0;
        for(auto &q : queries) {
            int type = q[0];
            int x = q[1];
            if(type == 0) {
                arr.push_back(x ^ xr);
            }
            else {
                xr ^= x;
            }
        }
        for(int &x : arr) {
            x ^= xr;
        }
        sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());
        return arr;
    }
};
	Key Insight
A global XOR operation affects every element equally. Instead of updating the entire array each time, keep a lazy XOR value `xr`. Store inserted elements as `x ^ xr`, and at the end apply the final XOR once to every element. This reduces repeated updates from O(q²) to O(q).
